{"title_page": "Rugby union in Madagascar", "text_new": "{{Sport overview\n| country               = Madagascar\n| sport                 = rugby unon\n| image                 = \n| imagesize             = 300px\n| caption               = \n| union                 = \n| nickname              = \n| first                 = 1890s\n| registered            = 22,540<ref name=\"IRB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irb.com/unions/union=11000071/index.html |title=International Rugby Board - MADAGASCAR |publisher=Irb.com |accessdate=2011-09-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930114132/http://www.irb.com/unions/union%3D11000071/index.html |archivedate=2011-09-30 }}</ref>\n| clubs                 = 410\n| match                 = \n| national_list         = [[Rugby World Cup]]<br/>[[Rugby World Cup Sevens]]<br/>[[Sevens World Series]]\n| club_list             = \n| countryflag           = Madagascar\n}}\n\n'''Rugby union in Madagascar''' is a popular team sport. As of September 2018, [[Madagascar national rugby union team|Madagascar]] is [[World Rugby Rankings|ranked]] 50th worldwide by [[World Rugby]] (WR),<ref name=\"runion rankings\">{{cite web| url=http://www.worldrugby.org/rankings|publisher=World Rugby |title=World Rankings |accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref> and boasts over 22,540 registered players and more than 410 rugby clubs.<ref>[http://www.irb.com/unions/union=11000071/index.html Official Madagascar Playing Numbers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930114132/http://www.irb.com/unions/union%3D11000071/index.html |date=2011-09-30 }}</ref> Although Madagascar lacks a professional competition as it is one of the poorest countries in the world, it does possess a national club competition that is extensively covered in the national print media, as well as having matches televised. \nRugby is considered the national sport of Madagascar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irb.com/newsmedia/regional/newsid=53025.html |accessdate=2012-07-27 |title=Madagascar take Sevens honours |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AGpxxkZd?url=http://www.irb.com/newsmedia/regional/newsid=53025.html |archivedate=2012-08-29 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planetrugby.com/story/0,25883,3891_7884390,00.html |accessdate=2012-07-27 |title=14-place jump for Madagascar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118094652/http://www.planetrugby.com/story/0%2C25883%2C3891_7884390%2C00.html |archivedate=2012-11-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe governing body is the F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Malagasy de Rugby.<ref name=\"IRB\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n[[Rugby union]] was introduced to [[Madagascar]] in the 1890s by [[France|French]] railroad workers who played the game in the capital, [[Antananarivo]], during the colonial period. Historically the sport was seen as a violent pastime of the poor, however recent developments have seen a huge increase in the sport's profile throughout the country.<ref>[http://www.theroar.com.au/2009/01/17/rugby-and-the-red-island-an-unlikely-union/ Rugby and the Red Island]</ref> The [[Madagascar national rugby union team|Madagascar]] team, locally referred to as the Makis (a [[Malagasy language|Malagasy]] word for the [[ring-tailed lemur]]), reached the finals of the 2005 Africa Cup, increasing nationwide interest in the sport.  Since then they have been semi-finalists in the [[2006 Africa Cup]] and finalists again in the [[2007 Africa Cup]].\n\nMadagascar is a founder member of the [[Confederation of African Rugby]] (CAR), which was launched officially in January 1986, in [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]. Rugby officials from [[Rugby union in Tunisia|Tunisia]], [[Rugby union in Morocco|Morocco]], [[Rugby union in Senegal|Senegal]], [[Rugby union in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire|Ivory Coast]], [[Rugby union in Tanzania|Tanzania]], [[Rugby union in Kenya|Kenya]], and [[Rugby union in the Seychelles|the Seychelles]] also attended.\n\n==Competitions==\nThe national club competition is structured along the same lines as the [[Nacional de Clubes|Argentine club championship]].  The regional unions within [[Madagascar]] send their top club(s) from the previous year's championship to compete in the nationwide top-flight league called the Top 8.\n\nThe national team also competes annually in the [[Africa Cup]], where matches sometimes double as [[Confederation of African Rugby]] [[Rugby World Cup]] qualifiers.\n\n==Popularity==\nIn addition to large participant numbers, rugby is popular with spectators in Madagascar. The Top 8 has average attendance figures of over 8,000, whilst the league final, and most international fixtures, attract crowds upward of 30,000 at the [[Mahamasina Municipal Stadium|Stade Municipal de Mahamasina]] in the capital. It is common that international rugby matches substantially outdraw those of [[Association football|football]] at the Mahamasina. Rugby's popularity is strongest in the central highlands region including Antananarivo.\n\nRugby union's popularity in the country was recently demonstrated during the Division 1B Final of the [[Africa Cup]], held in Madagascar.  Madagascar triumphed over [[Namibia national rugby union team|Namibia]] in front of 40,000 fans to stay in the qualification process for the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]] to be held in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/qualifying/news/newsid=2063227.html#madagascar+climb+rankings+after+shock| title=Madagascar climb rankings after shock win| date=9 July 2012| accessdate=21 July 2012| work=rugbyworldcup.com| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712120930/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/qualifying/news/newsid=2063227.html#madagascar+climb+rankings+after+shock| archivedate=12 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn Madagascar, rugby is a very popular sport among men. It is estimated that 60% of players in the country are men. The boys from Sapphire Coast and their captain Marcelia, backed by the French NGO Terres en M\u00eal\u00e9es are emerging as models for the development of women rugby in poor areas outside the capital city. They actually won twice the national girls championship. \nRugby is thus becoming a real tool to fight against poverty and develop gender equality in the country. Marcelia has been nominated one of the five most influential women of the country in 2019 by promoting development through rugby in Madagascar and in France.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Madagascar national rugby union team]]\n* [[Africa Cup]]\n* [[Confederation of African Rugby]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://twf.com.au/showthread.php?t=5170 Indian Ocean Rugby; Madagascar]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4471650.stm BBC News]\n* [http://www.worldrugby.org/member-unions/50 WR Madagascar page] \n*{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.lestimbresdurugby.com/Archivesdurugby/Pays/Madagascar.htm Archives du Rugby: Madagascar]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rugby union outside WC}}\n{{Africa in topic|Rugby union in}}\n\n[[Category:Rugby union in Madagascar|*]]\n[[Category:Sport in Madagascar]]\n", "text_old": "{{Sport overview\n| country               = Madagascar\n| sport                 = rugby union\n| image                 = \n| imagesize             = 300px\n| caption               = \n| union                 = \n| nickname              = \n| first                 = 1890s\n| registered            = 22,540<ref name=\"IRB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irb.com/unions/union=11000071/index.html |title=International Rugby Board - MADAGASCAR |publisher=Irb.com |accessdate=2011-09-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930114132/http://www.irb.com/unions/union%3D11000071/index.html |archivedate=2011-09-30 }}</ref>\n| clubs                 = 410\n| match                 = \n| national_list         = [[Rugby World Cup]]<br/>[[Rugby World Cup Sevens]]<br/>[[Sevens World Series]]\n| club_list             = \n| countryflag           = Madagascar\n}}\n\n'''Rugby union in Madagascar''' is a popular team sport. A